# Inheritance

Inheritance allows a class (child) to inherit properties and methods from another class (parent). Use the `extends` keyword.

```php
class Animal {
    public $name;

    public function eat() {
        echo "$this->name is eating.";
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    public function bark() {
        echo "$this->name says woof!";
    }
}

$dog = new Dog();
$dog->name = 'Buddy';
$dog->eat();   // from Animal
$dog->bark();  // from Dog
```

```php
<?php
class Vehicle {
    public $brand;

    public function start() {
        echo "Engine started.";
    }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    public $doors;

    public function honk() {
        echo "Beep beep!";
    }
}

$myCar = new Car();
$myCar->brand = 'Toyota';
$myCar->doors = 4;
$myCar->start();
$myCar->honk();
?>
```

# Overriding Parent Methods

A child class can redefine a method inherited from the parent. To call the parent's version, use `parent::`.

```php
class Animal {
    public function makeSound() {
        echo "Some sound";
    }
}

class Cat extends Animal {
    public function makeSound() {
        echo "Meow";
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    public function makeSound() {
        parent::makeSound(); // call parent
        echo " and also woof!";
    }
}
```
